@NODE "intro" "SnapIT - Introduction"
@PREV "main"
@NEXT "req"

 @{b}@{u}Introduction@{uu}@{ub}

 Why another screen shot tool you might ask ?


 I've always liked SGrab (by Stephan Rupprecht), basically I've liked the way
 it works, but not really the look of the GUI.
 So when I worked on another tool (using some of SnapIT's technologies) I
 thought, why not make a MUI-based screen snapper which is fully MorphOS native
 and has some nifty features ? =)

 So that's how SnapIT was born!

@ENDNODE

@NODE "req" "SnapIT - Requirements"
@PREV "intro"
@NEXT "install"

 @{b}@{u}Requirements@{uu}@{ub}

 This program needs some of the following systems to run :

 · MorphOS 2.x or higher
 · AmigaOS 4.1.6 or higher
 · AROS i386

@ENDNODE

@NODE "install" "SnapIT - Installation"
@PREV "req"
@NEXT "usage"

 @{b}@{u}Installation@{uu}@{ub}

 This program doesn't need any installation and because of that doesn't come with
 any form of installer script. Just place it where you want and run it from there! =)

 If you have only just downloaded/unarchived the utility then it is UNREGISTERED, and
 when initially run will 'pop-up' a requester explaining how to register the program
 for FREE - by e-mail. Please do so, as this will allow you to remove this slight
 annoyance on starting the program, and show in the 'About' requester that it is
 registered to you.

 By registering my program, which I hope you will find useful, it will also allow me to
 'guesstimate' how many people are using my utility, and for which platform(s). 

@ENDNODE

@NODE "usage" "SnapIT - Usage"
@PREV "install"
@NEXT "faq"

 @{b}@{u}Usage@{uu}@{ub}

 This program's user interface consists of a couple of fields/elements,
 which are briefly explained below...


 @{b}· Screen List :@{ub}

   This is a list containing all of your systems open screens.
   By double-clicking on the name in the list, the program tries to snap the chosen screen.


 @{b}· Window List :@{ub}

   This is the same as the Screen List above, only that these are the available windows on
   the current selected screen.


 @{b}· Preview :@{ub}

   This is a small preview window displaying the captured screen data.
   Clicking with the left-mouse button on the preview image will display it scaled 1:1 - so
   retaining its captured size/aspect ratio.


 @{b}· Save Image :@{ub}
 
   This button will become available (unghosted) as soon as there is image data stored in the buffer.
   Pressing this button will save the image where specified in the Settings window.


 @{b}· Preferences :@{ub}

   This is where you customise your use of SnapIT.
   Currently available options are:

    @{b}Capture Delay@{ub} - Here you define the time the program waits after it is hidden
    to actually grab the graphic data.

    @{b}Save Path@{ub} - The path where the saved images will be stored.

    @{b}Filename@{ub} - The name of the resulting image you want to save.
    Here you can adjust the name with some built-in variable templates.

    The templates are : 
    %w = Image width (pixels)
    %h = Image height (pixels)
    %d = Image depth (pixels)
    %x = Image extension (depends on what you have selected as an output format)
    %c = Snap counter (which is the counter value of the grabbed image, if you capture a whole series for example)

    @{b}Preview@{ub} - This is a preview of the Save Path and Filename combined.

    @{b}Format@{ub} - The image format that is used to create the output file.

    Available formats :
    · PNG
    · JPEG (here you can also set the compression quality, higher value = better quality, but larger file)

    @{b}Save image automatically@{ub} - If this is active, your captured data will automatically be saved to the specified location.


 @{b}· Free Grab Mode :@{ub}

   From here you select how the free grab mode will operate.
   Currently available options are:

    @{b}Active Screen@{ub} - If this option is selected the free grab will operate on the Ambient screen SnapIT currently displays.

    @{b}Selected Screen@{ub} - Making this option active allows free grab to operate on the screen you've selected from the screen list.


 @{b}· SnapIT-Window :@{ub}

    @{b}Open during grab@{ub} - This keeps the SnapIT window open while operating the screen grab.

    @{b}Closed during grab@{ub} - This closes the SnapIT window during the screen grab.


 @{b}· Hotkey - Screen capture :@{ub}

    Here you set your hotkey combination to activate the "Screen capture" functionality.
    
@{b}NOTE:@{ub} MorphOS users can use the sample-key button (right of the string field) to automatically
      discover the key combination you want/pressed.


 @{b}· Hotkey - Window capture :@{ub}

     Here you set your hotkey combination to activate the "Window capture" functionality.


 @{b}· Hotkey - Free capture :@{ub}

     Here you set your hotkey combination to activate the "Free capture" functionality.

 @{b}Tooltypes :@{ub}

   If you would like to specify the colour of the 'lasso' in free grab mode there is a tooltype option that
   you need to use to override the normal invert selection colour used by the lasso.
   
   Usage : LASSOCOLOUR=0xRRGGBB, meaning you have to specify the required pen colour as hex value.
   Example : 0xFF0000 = Red ; 0x00FF00 = Green ; 0x0000FF = Blue
   
   You can of course modify these to suit your own preferences.


 @{b}ARexx :@{ub}

   SnapIT has a small set of ARexx-commands built-in, which can affect the function of the
   program using scripts or a single line from an ARexx-command.

    @{b}grabscreen@{ub}
    This initiates a normal screengrab using the program.

    @{b}grabwindow@{ub}
    This grabs the currently selected window from the window list.

    @{b}grabactivewindow@{ub}
    This grabs the currently active window.

    @{b}freegrab@{ub}
    Using this gives the same result as pressing the Free Grab button.

    @{b}saveimage@{ub}
    Using this gives the same result as pressing the Save Image button.

    @{b}filepath <arg>@{ub}
    This command changes the Save Path string in the program's Settings.

    @{b}filename <arg>@{ub}
    This command changes the Filename string in the program's Settings.

    @{b}delay <arg>@{ub}
    This command changes the capture delay in the program's Settings. (valid input-values = 0...10)

    @{b}quality <arg>@{ub}
    This command changes the JPEG quality percentage in the program's Settings. (valid input-values = 0 to 100)


    Apart from the commands above, the normal MUI commands work as well.
    QUIT, HIDE, SHOW etc...


    To test the ARexx-interface, start SnapIT and open up a shell window.
    at the prompt type :

    rx "OPTIONS RESULTS; ADDRESS SNAPIT.1; 'delay 2'"

    This command line example will change the capture delay to 2 seconds.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "faq" "SnapIT - FAQ"
@PREV "usageprefs"
@NEXT "news"

@{b}@{u}FAQ - Frequently Asked Questions@{uu}@{ub}

* @{b}Q = Question@{ub}
* @{b}A = Answer@{ub}

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Q - Using Free Grab with "Selected Screen" -option with the "other" screen
    having another resolution than the current one running SnapIT may look
    strange (either by multiplying the gfx. or cutting the data grabbed). ?

A - This is a known issue and will be adressed in a later release.
    The solution, for now, is to grab the whole screen instead of just part of it.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------


@ENDNODE

@NODE "news" "SnapIT - What's new?"
@PREV "usage"
@NEXT "history"

 @{b}@{u}What's new@{uu}@{ub}

 · Double buffered preview mode -> less flicker when scaling the window...
 · Added an adjustable vertical bar to allow the GUI to predominantly be Screen/Window gadget list or Preview =)
 · Hotkey support (screen, window and free grab)
 · Fetch active window (via AREXX command) - grabactivewindow
 · Clicking on the preview image results in a new window with the unscaled image data as a 1:1 preview.
 · The position of the window list is kept intact after a screen grab.
 · Added "Save image as..." menu option.
 · Cancel button in preferences actually works now =)
 · Small GUI adjustments (removed the option for Lasso Colour and more)
 · Added LASSOCOLOUR-tooltype for users who really want to be able to set this.
 · Added an option to save an image automatically after capture.
 · Small locale adjustments
 · Added Spanish translation by Dámaso Domínguez
 · Added German translation by Thomas Blatt
 · Added French translation by Guillaume Boesel

@ENDNODE

@NODE "history" "SnapIT - History"
@PREV "news"
@NEXT "future"

 @{b}@{u}History@{uu}@{ub}

 · 30-Jul-2005

   * Started to code the first draft for SnapIT


 · 07-Aug-2005

   * First official release of SnapIT (v0.1), Released at the PUSH-event in Gothenburg


 · 15-Sep-2005 - Second release (v0.2)

   * Ability to snap other screens than Public screens.
   * Window snapping enabled.
   * Auto-refreshing screen/window list(s).
   * A slightly different GUI-design.
   * More detailed documentation.
   * Added Spanish documentation by Victor Gutiérrez


· 26-Oct-2013 - Third release (v1.0)

   * New preview mode, keeping the image aspect of the grabbed content.
   * Free Grab option.
   * AREXX support.
   * Locale support
   * Recognise unnamed windows by their task or process name.
   * Added an icon for the program made by Itzik Gur (My Seven Icons).


· 27-Oct-2013 - Fourth release (v1.1)

   * Corrected a bug which caused a hit when the screenblanker kicked in.
   * Spelling/Grammar correction on the documentation done by Neil Pearson


· 18-Nov-2013 - Fifth release (v1.2)

   * AmigaOS4 support.
   * AROS support.
   * Updated JPEG/PNG-save routines.
   * Work-around for missing ScalePixelArray()-function in AROS.
   * Filtered out backdrop windows to avoid crashes.
   * Fix to erase old preview data when new one is overlapping.
   * New icon set from Thomas Blatt (found in icons-drawer).
   * Italian translation by Samir Hawamdeh.
   * Added keyfile support, functionality is not crippled (don't worry) =) 


· 27-Jan-2014 - Sixth release (v1.3)

   * Double buffered preview mode -> less flicker when scaling the window...
   * Added an adjustable vertical bar to allow the GUI to predominantly be Screen/Window gadget list or Preview =)
   * Hotkey support (screen, window and free grab)
   * Fetch active window (via AREXX command) - grabactivewindow
   * Clicking on the preview image results in a new window with the unscaled image data as a preview.
   * The position of the window list is now kept intact after a screen grab.
   * Added "Save image as..." menu option.
   * Cancel button in Settings actually works now =)
   * Small GUI adjustments (removed the option for Lasso Colour and more)
   * Added LASSOCOLOUR-tooltype for users who really want to be able to set this.
   * Added an option to save an image automatically after capture.
   * Small locale adjustments
   * Added Spanish translation by Dámaso Domínguez
   * Added German translation by Thomas Blatt
   * Added French translation by Guillaume Boesel

@ENDNODE

